03273nmm a2200505Ia 9780791484241DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97807914842417 a10.1515/97807914842412doi  a(DE-B1597)683680  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aB105.F29bS75 2005 7aPHI0010002bisacsh04a128/.62221 aStimilli, Davide, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Face of Immortality :bPhysiognomy and Criticism /cDavide Stimilli. 1aAlbany : bSUNY Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (217 p.) :bTotal Illustrations: 0  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSUNY series, Intersections: Philosophy and Critical Theory0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe literature on physiognomy—the art of studying a person's outward appearance, especially the face, in order to determine character and intelligence—has flourished in recent years in the wake of renewed scholarly interest in the history and politics of the body. Virtually no attention, however, has been devoted to the vocabulary and rhetoric of physiognomy. The Face of Immortality addresses this gap, arguing that the trend in Western culture has been to obliterate the face, which is manifested in criticism as a disregard for the letter.Denouncing this trend, Davide Stimilli draws on Hebrew, Greek, Latin, Italian, English, and German sources in order to explore the terminology and historical development of physiognomy. Stimilli takes physiognomy to be the resistance to such an obliteration of the face, and argues that it offers a model for a theory of reading that does not discount the letter as inessential. Elaborating on the work of Walter Benjamin, he defines the task of physiognomical criticism as transliteration (which preserves the letter) rather than translation (which obliterates it). The Face of Immortality is meant to exemplify the method and test the reach of such a criticism, which aims at mediating between philology and philosophy, between literal and allegorical modes of interpretation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aFace (Philosophy). 0aPhysiognomy. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Art Theory. 4aLiterature : Comparative Literature. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy of Literature. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Aesthetics.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978079148424140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791484241423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791484241/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles